<subSubSection id="A2F865885F962D78C60D70BBE16087CF" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="A65FAB8B5CA4A44516DA2C2BD25160E8" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Genus 
<taxonomicName id="5462E1819961902352A7FE78374F9F4B" LSID="4FEC636B-4AE2-594C-96B2-1B61D9F9043F" authority="O. Pickard-Cambridge, 1869" authorityName="O. Pickard-Cambridge" authorityYear="1869" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Stephanopis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stephanopis" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stephanopis O. Pickard-Cambridge, 1869</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C51C3C16F8C02D0E1E34474C4D68E649" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="comments">
<paragraph id="A1A238006B706AF3EE4DA602AF218A5C" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AE9F2EFFF184867D3C6F352B4FABE8E9" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
This genus includes 23 species (
<bibRefCitation id="BE4F6E1DFC343EC145DA7776EB71E18B" author="World Spider Catalog" journalOrPublisher="Oriental Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" publicationUrl="https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" refId="B24" refString="World Spider Catalog, 2022. World Spider Catalog. Natural History Museum Bern. Version 22.5. https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" title="World Spider Catalog. Natural History Museum Bern. Version 22.5." url="https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" year="2022">WSC 2022</bibRefCitation>
). Most of them are distributed in South America, Oceania, Australia, and Papua New Guinea (
<bibRefCitation id="5AFD5E1CD0CCA914667A66F1BE9771BE" author="World Spider Catalog" journalOrPublisher="Oriental Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" publicationUrl="https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" refId="B24" refString="World Spider Catalog, 2022. World Spider Catalog. Natural History Museum Bern. Version 22.5. https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" title="World Spider Catalog. Natural History Museum Bern. Version 22.5." url="https://wsc.nmbe.ch/" year="2022">WSC 2022</bibRefCitation>
). The recent phylogenetic analyses based on a matrix of 117 morphological characters scored for 77 terminal taxa have revealed a large variation in morphology among 
<taxonomicName id="84A6252671698BAF6577E0D486D328D4" authorityName="O. Pickard-Cambridge" authorityYear="1869" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Stephanopis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stephanopis" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8BEACE254885E5FDD380499F90E180B7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Stephanopis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation id="D10EFDDF66D31E4A5B134EEB4A63606A" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-020-00472-x" author="Machado, M" journalOrPublisher="Organisms, Diversity &amp; Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" pagination="281 - 313" refId="B10" refString="Machado, M, Teixeira, RA, 2021. Phylogenetic relationships in Stephanopinae: systematics of Stephanopis and Sidymella based on morphological characters (Araneae: Thomisidae). Organisms, Diversity &amp; Evolution 21 (2): 281 - 313, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-020-00472-x" title="Phylogenetic relationships in Stephanopinae: systematics of Stephanopis and Sidymella based on morphological characters (Araneae: Thomisidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-020-00472-x" volume="21" year="2021">Machado and Teixeira 2021</bibRefCitation>
); these taxonomic revisions have greatly contributed to a better understanding of the group. Here we report the first species from the Asian continent as well as from the entire Oriental zoogeographical realm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
